title: (0.6.x Backport) Multiple speed improvements revolving around topN with HLL
body:
(Backport)

Change serializer / deserializer for HyperLogLog
- Changed DirectDruidClient's InputStream handling. Is now ~10% faster for data heavy queries, and has lower variance in execution speed.
- Changed HLL Collector's toByteStream() method to be better optimized for small values. Is notably faster for small result quantities which fall into the sparse HLL bucket codepath.
  - No change for dense HLL which just uses a direct bytestream of the underlying byte data.

TopNNumericResultBuilder semi-aggressive loop unrolling for metricVals

title: Replace AppendableByteArrayInputStream in DirectDruidClient
body:
- Replace with SequenceInputStream fueled by an enumeration of ChannelBufferInputStream which directly wrap the response context ChannelBuffer

I was seeing a lot of issues with the micro-byte[ ] allocations. This PR is an attempt to get around that limitation.

The use case where I was able to get it to show up most dramatically is when there are a few thousand segments in a topN query with populate cache enabled.

title: Task thread priority
body:
- Defaults the thread priority to java.util.Thread.NORM_PRIORITY in io.druid.indexing.common.task.AbstractTask
- Each exec service has its own Task Factory which is assigned a priority for spawned task. Therefore each priority class has a unique exec service

Supposedly: on Oracle JVM this is only activated when setting `-XX:+UseThreadPriorities` and running the JVM as root, or setting `-XX:+UseThreadPriorities -XX:ThreadPriorityPolicy=42` (where 42 is any number neither 0 nor 1). See [this thread](http://www.akshaal.info/2008/04/javas-thread-priorities-in-linux.html)

title: TopN performance improvements
body:
## How the aggressive loop unrolling works:
- Each aggregator's offset into the stream is calculated and stored
- Most queries have fewer than 8 aggregates, this allows them to be executed in a simple switch statement. (See [Duff's Device](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Duff's_device) for more info on this type of approach).
- If there are more than 8 aggregates, then they are executed in blocks of 8, with the "leftover" non-divisible-by-8 aggregates being evaluated first.

Re-factor scanAndAggregate in PooledTopN
- Loops are now a little bit tighter when looping over aggregates. This will hopefully assist in loop execution optimization.
- Pre-calculated the aggregate offsets instead of shifting them during runtime.
- Cursor loop could use some TLC, but would require a massive refactoring on how TopN queries are executed.
- Any potential modifications to query workflow need to account for Stream vs Batch data, and that not all data will be array backed that comes in.
- Changed looping to attempt to do 8 at a time for both aggregates and dim values
- Any dim value collection or aggregate collection with less than 8 at a time, or the remainder of values which are not evenly divisible by 8, has values serviced by a SWITCH statement rather than looping anything.

Change data storage type in TopNNumericResultBuilder.
- Use PriorityQueue to store
- Checks to see if should even bother adding to Queue before adding.
- Re-orders Queue on build() call.
- Ideally the order would be directly preserved on build(), but this is a close second.

General performance improvements:

TopN multivalue multi aggregate: just shy of 30% faster

TopN multivalue single aggregate: just shy of 5% faster

title: Support more AWS credentials providers for S3 storage
body:
Build an AWS credentials provider chain that looks for credentials in this order:
- ConfigDrivenAwsCredentialsConfigProvider - the existing druid configuration file (accessKey+secretKey)
- LazyFileSessionCredentialsProvider - the existing druid configuration file (fileSessionCredentials)
- EnvironmentVariableCredentialsProvider - system environment variables (AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID and AWS_SECRET_KEY)
- SystemPropertiesCredentialsProvider - Java System Properties (aws.accessKeyId and aws.secretKey)
- ProfileCredentialsProvider - Credential profiles file at the default location (~/.aws/credentials)
- InstanceProfileCredentialsProvider - Instance profile credentials delivered through the Amazon EC2 metadata service
